<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is Naismith's rule?", answer: "Naismith's rule is a simple formula devised in 1892 by Scottish mountaineer William W. Naismith to estimate hiking time: allow one hour for every 5 kilometers (3 miles) of distance on flat ground, plus an additional hour for every 600 meters (2000 feet) of ascent. It is the most widely used rough hiking time estimator in the English-speaking world and is the default baseline for route cards in Scottish Mountain Leader training, British Duke of Edinburgh's Award expeditions, and many outdoor guidebooks." },
  { question: "Does Naismith's rule account for descent?", answer: "Original Naismith does not adjust for descent. Descent on gentle slopes actually speeds you up slightly, but descent on steep or slippery ground slows you down considerably due to the care required to stay safe. This calculator adds a simple descent adjustment based on Langmuir's correction: 10 minutes added per 300 meters of descent. For rough or rocky descents, you should add even more time, because Langmuir's correction underestimates the effort of steep descents." },
  { question: "Should I trust Naismith's estimate?", answer: "Naismith's rule is a planning baseline, not a precision tool. It assumes you are reasonably fit, carrying a light pack, walking on a good path in good weather. Heavy packs, bad weather, difficult terrain, group travel, rest breaks, photography, and navigation all slow you down. For conservative planning, multiply Naismith time by 1.25 to 1.5. Experienced mountaineers sometimes divide by 0.8 for fast-and-light alpine trips. Always compare against your own times on similar routes to build a personal correction factor." },
  { question: "What fitness levels does the calculator support?", answer: "The calculator offers four fitness levels: fast (0.80× multiplier, for experienced fit hikers on easy ground), normal (1.00×, standard Naismith), moderate (1.25×, for less experienced hikers or heavier loads), and slow (1.50×, for leisurely pace or difficult conditions). These multipliers are applied to the base Naismith calculation after adding ascent and descent adjustments, giving you a realistic range for planning purposes." },
  { question: "How does terrain affect hiking time?", answer: "Terrain can dramatically change your actual time. Paved paths and wide trails let you move at full Naismith speed. Rooty or rocky paths slow you by 10 to 20 percent. Scrambling sections can double your time. Snow, ice, mud, thick brush, and off-trail bushwhacking all add significant delays. As a rule of thumb, add 20 percent for moderately rough terrain, 50 percent for rough terrain, and 100 percent or more for very rough or technical terrain." }
]) %>

